      Ultimate endless shrimp
   =20
 =20

Here is a hypothetical move:
=09You are in the business of producing and selling shrimp.=09You expand ve=
rtically by acquiring a chain of seafood restaurants.=09The restaurants sta=
rt to=C2=A0struggle and are heavily indebted, and you worry that your equit=
y investment is losing value and possibly worthless.=09How to cut your loss=
es?=09Well, you have two relationships to the restaurant chain: You own the=
 equity, and you also supply the shrimp.=09Not much you can do with the equ=
ity: There=E2=80=99s a lot of debt, the creditors=C2=A0rank ahead of you, a=
nd they are unlikely to let you take any cash out as a dividend.=09But, as =
the equity owner, you also control the board of directors and get to appoin=
t the chief executive officer.=09The CEO decides how much shrimp to buy.=09=
What if he decided to buy a lot=C2=A0of shrimp?=09Then you=E2=80=99d make=
=C2=A0money on the shrimp, and extract at least some value out of your equi=
ty investment.

There is presumably some tipping point.=C2=A0There is some level where the =
restaurants are viable enough that you will want to operate them to maximiz=
e their equity value, but if they fall below that level, you will give up o=
n the equity=C2=A0and just try to maximize the shrimp consumption. In the f=
irst equilibrium, you will spend money carefully on=C2=A0shrimp and biscuit=
s and silverware and advertising, with the goal of increasing profitability=
. In the second equilibrium, you will spend money profligately and only on =
shrimp, with the goal of spending money on shrimp.
=E2=80=9CRed Lobster Chain Goes Bankrupt After Unlimited Shrimp Deal=E2=80=
=9D is the great=C2=A0Bloomberg News headline:

Seafood restaurant chain Red Lobster filed for bankruptcy, succumbing to on=
