I wrote last Thursday about two brothers who were charged with wire fraud f=
or doing an exploit on the Ethereum blockchain that allegedly earned them $=
25 million from arbitrage bots. Ordinarily here is where I would give a two=
-sentence summary of the story, but honestly it is complicated, and I would=
 advise you to either (1) read what I wrote last week or (2) skip the rest =
of this section.
If you are still here, though, I want to clarify two points based on emails=
 I got from readers.
First, though I described the exploit as =E2=80=9Cfront-running the front-r=
unners,=E2=80=9D I do want to be clear that it was=C2=A0not=C2=A0just=C2=A0=
that. This is not a=C2=A0pure=C2=A0case of (1) submitting spoofy orders to =
bait=C2=A0front-running bots, (2) having them take the bait and (3) finding=
 some trade to make them lose money. (There=C2=A0are=C2=A0prior examples of=
 that, using oddly structured tokens to make the front-runners lose money.)=
 Here, though, the brothers are accused of something closer to hacking, exp=
loiting a weakness in software code to be able to see (and reorder) a serie=
s of transactions that was supposed to be kept confidential from them. That=
=C2=A0is=C2=A0worse; it=E2=80=99s sort of like the difference between (1) p=
utting in spoof orders on the stock exchange to try to trick a high-frequen=
cy trading firm and (2) hacking into the stock exchange=E2=80=99s computer =
system to reverse the HFT firm=E2=80=99s trades. Even if you think that the=
 front-running bots are bad, you might =E2=80=94=C2=A0as the Justice Depart=
ment does =E2=80=94=C2=A0object to this approach to punishing them.
Second, I said that =E2=80=9Cthey exploited a bug in Ethereum=E2=80=9D to d=
o this, but that=E2=80=99s not quite right. They exploited a bug in Flashbo=
ts=E2=80=99 MEV-Boost, open-source block-building software that =E2=80=9Cap=
proximately 90% of Ethereum validators use=E2=80=9D but that is not part of=
 the core Ethereum system itself. (Here is Flashbots=E2=80=99 explanation.)=
 They exploited a bug in how blocks are normally built and proposed on Ethe=
reum. From the names =E2=80=9CFlashbots=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CMEV-Boost,=E2=
=80=9D though, you might get some sense of why the case is controversial. T=
he way that blocks are normally built and proposed on Ethereum involves =E2=
=80=9Cmaximal extractable value=E2=80=9D (MEV), where arbitrage traders bid=
 to pay validators for priority to make the most profitable trades. These b=
rothers hacked=C2=A0that=C2=A0system, but not everyone likes that system, b=
ecause it involves predatory traders front-running more naive traders.=C2=
=A0
This is also important because, as one reader commented: =E2=80=9CA=C2=A0a =
crucial distinguishing factor here is that James and Anton did not re-order=
=C2=A0committed=C2=A0transactions; they instead picked an ordering of=C2=A0=
pending=C2=A0transactions that were favorable to them. Under this lens, the=
 integrity of the blockchain is not compromised; the network explicitly =E2=
=80=98allows=E2=80=99 validators to pick whatever arbitrary ordering of tra=
nsactions they like; it's just that generally it=E2=80=99s economically fav=
orable for validators to prioritize transactions which pay them the most fi=
rst.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Elsewhere, here is a good and balanced=C2=A0CoinDesk article about why this=
 case is controversial:

MEV, which itself is controversial, can be a highly lucrative game dominate=
d by automated bots that often comes at blockchain users=E2=80=99 expense, =
which is partially why so many in the crypto community have rushed to denou=
nce the DOJ=E2=80=99s complaint. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThey used a flaw in MEV boost to push invalid signatures to previe=
w bundles. That gives an unfair advantage via an exploit,=E2=80=9D former e=
