<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Starting from Dec. 30, chocolate makers that s=
ell or produce in the EU will have to show that the cocoa they use wasn=E2=
=80=99t grown on land cut from forests since the end of 2020. In practice, =
it means that each morsel of cocoa that makes its way into the bloc will ne=
ed to be linked to the GPS coordinates of the farm where it was harvested.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s where people like [Brice-Armel]=
 Konan, who helps monitor cocoa farm data in Ivory Coast for the Rainforest=
 Alliance, a nonprofit based in New York and Amsterdam, and his smartphone =
come in. Such nonprofits, along with industry groups, governments and choco=
late companies, are racing to help farmers record the data they need in tim=
e.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ivory Coast=E2=80=99s cocoa and coffee regulat=
or says it has mapped just over 80% of the country=E2=80=99s estimated 1.55=
 million cocoa farms. That leaves some 300,000=E2=80=94or about 2,000 a day=
=E2=80=94to be mapped or otherwise accounted for by Oct. 1, the start of th=
e new cocoa season.</p>
</blockquote>
